SIMPLE: elongate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elongate
<hw>E*lon"gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Elongated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Elongating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL.
<ets>elongatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>elongare</ets> to remove, to
prolong; <ets>e</ets> + L. <ets>longus</ets> long. See <er>Long</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Eloign</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
lengthen; to extend; to stretch; <as>as, to <ex>elongate</ex> a
line</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove further off.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elongate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Elongate
<hw>E*lon"gate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To depart to, or be at, a
distance; esp., to recede apparently from the sun, as a planet in its
orbit.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elongate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Elongate
<hw>E*lon"gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>elongatus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Drawn out at length; elongated;
<as>as, an <ex>elongate</ex> leaf</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An
<xex>elongate</xex> form.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Earle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>elongated</ent>⟦br⟧
